The paper focuses on attributed network embedding, which involves learning low-dimensional representations of nodes that preserve both topology and attribute information. This topic is relevant to several sub-categories in computer science, including social and information networks (cs.SI), machine learning (cs.LG), statistical learning (cs.SD), data structures and algorithms (cs.DS), and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). Given that the paper proposes a novel generative model for attributed network embedding that outperforms existing methods on both clustering and classification tasks, it is likely to be of interest to researchers in these sub-fields.
